IMS Curriculum survey

Gavin Fay, Geoff Cowles

September 11, 2018

Overview

As part of the response for the AQAD implementation plan for SMAST/IMS, a survey was distributed to IMS faculty to obtain information on course offerings, with a goal to provide resources for students on timing of course offerings and availability, and perform gap analysis on the SMAST curriculum.

Analysis of survey results

A total of

## [1] 32

responses were submitted. This does not cover all the current offerings within our curriculum.

Summaries of some of the responses are provided below:

A large number of graduate courses are intended to be offered every academic year, and most of the courses included in the survey results are active (taught within the last 2-3 academic years). There is a fair amount of flexibility in the targeting of courses to where students are during their program, though a substantial number of courses are intended to be taken in the first year of study. This may be incompatible with courseloads, but further analysis is needed (GF to remove core courses from this last panel).

Most courses are offered for 3 credits. 4 credit courses are generally those which include a lab section. 1 credit classes include the required graduate seminars.

Single courses meet the Biological, and Physical Oceanography IMS requirements (same for Chem Ocea requirement but results not part of survey). A small number of courses fulfill the policy requirement (only MAR 530 part of results), and these courses are offered regularly but coordination among offerings could be improved. The majority of courses do not fulfil current core course requirements, and in almost all cases, instructors indicated these elective courses did not satisfy these requirements. PSM requirements were not included in the survey. (GF to add detail on these)

Resources for students

A timetable of course names, instructors, when offered, and whether the courses meet core course requirements would be a useful resource for the SMAST & IMS websites to help both students and advisors with degree planning. A suggested format is provided below (though note this is incomplete due to only using survey results).
An additional useful resource would be suggested possible sequence/schedules of courses for students in the PSM / MS / and doctoral degree programs. Note that these would be to give prospective applicants a flavor of what coursework could look like within the program, rather than being prescriptive. Individual faculty will have their own ‘preferred’ menu of courses for students working in their research groups and areas of specialty. An additional list of courses in other departments and campuses that are available and relevant to IMS students could be provided or pointed to.
There has been some attempt to assign course numbers by topic and to separate 500 and 600 level courses. A recommendation moving forward would be to be stricter about this, perhaps an assignment of number ranges for certain course sequences / topics could be proposed. There have been a large number of recently taught special topics courses (e.g. 580) that are becoming a normal part of the regular curriculum. Instructors for these courses are encouraged to request a proper number to have these courses listed as their own course. Such a move will help to solidify the transparency of course offerings within the various IMS programs.
